[normal]It may be of interest to note that a
[normal] brief 
[normal]safety 
[normal]comparison 
[normal]was undertaken 
[normal]over a 3 year
[normal] 
[normal]period 
[normal](1979 – 1981
[normal] – see below
[normal]) between
[normal] World Jet Transport operations 
[normal]and Offshore H
[normal]elicopter operations
[normal].
[normal]  This brief comparison sho
[normal]wed that the offshore flying was 
[normal]relatively 
[normal]safer than the fixed wing worldwide public transport flying
[normal] during that three year period
[normal].
[normal]  It would perhaps be of further interest to do a similar comparison for the last five years
[normal] 
[normal](2009 – 2013[bold]) where the avera
[normal]ge 
[normal]offshore annual
[normal] 
[normal]flying 
[normal]hours were approximately 74,265 hours. 
[normal]During this period there were
[normal] 2 
[normal]x 
[normal]fatal accidents and 20 
[normal]x 
[normal]fatalities (
[normal]1 x[bold] fatality per 18,566 hours[bold] and 1 x fatal accident every 2.5 years)[bold] and this shows a lowering of the offshore safety standards when compared to earlier comparisons. In the following comparison the annual offshore helicopter hours flown are more than double the average totals over the last five years.
